\item Let $\vec{O}$ be the centre of the circle and $r$ be the radius of the circle. Since centre lies on the line, it satisfies the line equation
\begin{align}
\myvec{1&-3}\vec{O} = 11
\label{eq:eq1}
\end{align}

\item Also the circle passes through $\myvec{2\\3} and \myvec{-1\\1}$.Let these points be $\vec{P}$ and $\vec{Q}$ repectively. So the distance between centre and these points will be equal to the radius.
\begin{align}
\norm{\vec{P} - \vec{O}} = \norm{\vec{Q}- \vec{O}} = r 
\end{align}
On solving we get the equation
\begin{align}
\myvec{6&4}\vec{O} = 11
\label{eq:eq2}
\end{align}

\item The equations from \eqref{eq:eq1} and \eqref{eq:eq2}, can be solved to get $\vec{O}$.
\begin{align}
\myvec{1&-3\\6&4}\vec{O} &= \myvec{11\\11} \\
\vec{O} &= \myvec{1&-3\\6&4}^{-1}\myvec{11\\11} \\
\vec{O} &= \frac{1}{22}\myvec{77\\-55}
\end{align}
Hence $\vec{O}$ = $\myvec{\frac{7}{2}\\\frac{-5}{2}}$

\item Sustituting $\vec{O}$ we get $r$= 5.7
\item Equation of circle is 
\begin{align}
\norm{\vec{x}- \vec{O}}= 5.7
\end{align}
